value.value: The rhabdoms of most insects are cylindrical in form and act as light guides, i.e. they trap and retain light by total internal reflection. The cone of light that such a cylinder can trap is narrow. The acceptance angle of the cylinder is limited by the critical angle for total internal reflection, and therefore is governed by the differenece of refractive index between the receptor itself and the surrounding cytoplasm.

In some bodies of water, but not all, the water surface is a hazardous place due to predators. Larvae gain protection by a variety of means, including the occupation of transient biotopes, which often lack predators, or avoidance responses given to surface vibration or visual stimuli.
They are an important part of feeding behaviour, causing larvae to remain in the location of food sources.
When the turning increases with stimulus strength.
When the turning decreases with stimulus strength.

When the movement decreases with stimulus strength.
Refers to egg production that is dependent on protein intake.
Egg production in the absence of all adult feeding.

definition.value: Autogeny is genetically determined, nevertheless environmental and other non-genetic factors play an important role on its expression. The females that are genetically autogenous do not invariably initiate vitellogenic ovarian development in the absence of blood feeding.

value.value: Observed in genetically autogenous females that will engorge readily during the first ovarian cycle if they meet a host, but which can mature one batch of eggs without a blood meal.
Observed in females that do not engorge during the first ovarian cycle, even when hosts are available.
The condition in which a female is inseminated by only a single male.
The emergence of males before females into a seasonal breeding population.

definition.value:
Species for which protandry has been recorded in wild populations include Aedes communis, Aedes impiger, Aedes nigripes, Aedes sierrensis and Aedes vittatus.
Is widespread among insects and a number of reasons have been suggested for its evolution, for example, the prevention of inbreeding, the enhancement of reproductive success in males that emerge early, and natural selection for sexual size dimorphism.

value.value: The condition in which a female is inseminated by more than one male.

label.value: senses and flight response during mating

value.value: Flight reactions and patterns expressed during mating.
The males of species that mate in flight fly towards a conspecific female when stimulated by her flight tone.

definition.value: Mating is initiated with the male and female still in flight. It may end with the pair still in flight or settled on vegetation or on the ground, but usually copulation is completed within seconds.

value.value: The signal to which male mosquitoes respond is the female's flight tone, and this a flying female can never switch off.

definition.value: Considering as a means of sound production, the wing beat has a very low efficiency, and the distance over which the flight sounds of female mosquitoes can be detected by conspecific males probably is not greater than about 30cm.

label.value: response of olfactory sensillum during mating

value.value: The females of some insects emit long-range signals when sexual receptive, and switch off these signals when unreceptive.

label.value: response to visual stimulus during mating

Within 24h of a first blood meal, the epithilial cells of the calyx become flattened and extended and start to develop microvilli, the calyx lumen becomes greatly enlarged, and the calyx assumes the shape of a distened sac. The muscle cells of the calyx undergo rather little development. During this period changes start in the lateral oviducts also, reaching completion by 72h post-blood meal. A distinct lumen forms within each lateral oviduct, the epithelium becomes folded, providing for distension of the lateral oviduct at ovulation, and the luminal surface of the epithelial cells becomes microvillate. The muscles cells grow substantially in volume, and their myofibrils and mitochondria increase in number and degree of organization.

definition.value: The process described concernes Aedes aegypti. In Anopheles, the columnar epithelium of the ampullae is thrown into folds during the first ovarian cycle. During this and each succeeding ovarian cycle the size of the ampullae increases due to accumulation of secretion within the columnar cells.

value.value: The quality of forming and moving in a swarm.

definition.value: Most reports of swarming mosquitoes concern species of Anopheles, Culex and Aedes. Swarming has been described also in species of Psorophora, Culiseta, Uranotaenia, Armigeres and Coquilletidia. All mosquito swarms have 3 characteristics in common: 1) The individual members of a swarm fly in looping or zig-zag patterns characteristic of the species, and all keep within a limited space that is located in relation to some feature of the environment. 2) The swarms consist predominately of males. When conspecifics females enter a swarm, males approach and attempt to couple with them. 3) Swarming is limited to times of day characteristic of the species, usually close to dusk and dawn.

value.value: It occurs at a considerable height above the ground and extend over a large area like a ceiling. It develops only when there are extremely large numbers of males participanting.

definition.value: Ceiling swarms are not station-keeping swarms, although they make give rise to them.

value.value: Occurs in areas of open ground and form over swarm markers. Free swarms reappear, day after day, over position that have no characteristics discernible to human eyes.

definition.value: Swarms of Anopheles gambiae and An arabiensis formed over parts of flat, open ground within an area of scattered huts and trees.

value.value: Occurs in areas of open ground and forms over small areas of visual contrast, for example over patches of paler or darker earth, piles of dunk, bushes, small pools etc.

definition.value: Changes in reflectance can lead to swarm markers being deserted. Some permanent swarm markers may be used by a species year after year.

value.value: Forms within breaks in vegetation or at vegetational boundaries, and may be within a range of elevations. The flight paths are delineated by vegetational boundaries or by shafts of sunlight within the breaks.
Forms over prominent vertical ojects, such a tree tops, chimneys or church steeples.

A pheromone is any chemical or set of chemicals produced by a living organism that transmits a message to other members of the same species. Sex pheromones indicate the availability of the female for breeding.

definition.value:
The involvement of sex pheromones in species recognition by mosquitoes has been postulated by a number of authors but usually has not been confirmed by experimental investigation.
There is evidence for the presence of a contact peromone on the legs of females of the Culiseta inormata. Contact with isolated female legs was sufficient to release coupling behaviour in males. The active substance was non-volatile, heat-stable, and soluble in solvents of intermediate polarity.

value.value: The male and female behavioural patterns for sexual stimuli after the completion of their sexual maturation.

The ability of a male to inseminate a number of females depends upon the supply of both spermatozoa and accessory gland secretion. The average male could fully inseminate four to five females and transmit small amounts of sperm to an additional two to four females.

definition.value: Reports of insemination that do not quantify sperm transfer are of only limited value.

value.value: Once a female mosquito has undergone a consummated union she usually becomes refractory to further mating, at least until after completing a gonotropic cycle. Female sexual refractoriness has immediate and delayed components.
A strongly cyclic adult behaviour, and most species swarm for short periods around sunset and sunrise. The pattern of flight is specific.

The lower level of station-keeping swarms reflects the pattern of the individual members. A swarming mosquito flies in a particula pattern an often, for a number of seconds or longer, remains within a small space as thought it were confined in a box.

definition.value:
Swarms usually consist of a number of individuals, but single mosquitoes may exhibit swarming behaviour. The presence of other mosquitoes can only modify this behaviour.
Light wind can influence the orientation of swarming mosquitoes.

value.value: A characteristic of sabethines is that the males patrol the area of vegetation in which conspecific females rest. Of species that assembly in station-keeping swarms, the males and females may rest in the same places, and contact between males and females after arousal can lead to mating.

definition.value: The vegetation in which conspecific females rest are often the vertical and horizontal surfaces of tree trunks, stems or branches.

value.value: The mechanisms that prevent development of another series of follicles in gravid females.

In mosquitoes, egg production is a cyclic process. Batches of sister follicles is separate successively from the germania of the many ovarioles, and the follicles of each batch develop synchronously through a sequence of steps until the oocytes they contain are fully formed. The steps from the formation of a batch of mature oocytes constitute an ovarian cycle.

definition.value: The most important developmental events during an ovarian cycle are: (i) differentiation of the oocytes. (ii) reductional division of the oocytes' chromosomes. (iii) Synthesis of RNA by oocytes and nurse cells and its deposition in the ooplasm. (iv)Synthesis of yolk by the fat body and its deposition in the ooplasm. (v)Formation of the chorion.

value.value: The gates are points of potential or actual arrest at which follicular development will be halted, without detriment to the follicles, unless or until specific physiological conditions occur. These might entail exposure to specific stimuli or, conceptually at least, the absence of specific inhibitors.

This description of ovarian stages is based on the development of primary ovarian follicles in Ae aegypti and Cx pipiens. Anopheles gambie shows the following differences: there is no distinct stage Ib characterized by differnces between oocyte and nurse cells, and by stage IIa the oocyte half fills the follicle.

label.value: ovarian developmental stages according Troy et al.

value.value: The ovarian cycle can be divided into sequential phases and stages using physiological and anatomical criteria.

In the earliest stage at which ovarian follicles are visibly distinct they are still closely attached to the germaria (Christopher's stage G). Normally the primary follicles separate from the germaria shortly after emergence, and each subsequent batch of follicles leaves the germarial reting stage when a blood meal restarts the ovarian cycle.

Oocytes that have reached stage V and are ready for ovulation are often described as mature, yet their chromosomes are still in the metaphase of the first meiotic division. Meiosis is resumed only after the oocytes have been penetrated by sperm at oviposition. Thus the oocytes are held in a state of nuclear stasis from the time they are ready for ovulation until syngamy stimulates completion of the maturation divisions. The maturation resting stage normally lasts only a few hours, until the appropriate activity rhythm leads to ovulation and oviposition. However, if females are unable to oviposit, the stage V oocytes can remain viable within ovaries for 15days or even more.

The primary follicles may develop directly to Christopher's stage IIa or IIb after emergence, or may develop to this stage only after the females have fed. The primary follicles of anautogenous females then enter the previtellogenic resting stage, remaining in it until the female has taken a blood meal. The primary follicles of autogenous females pass the previtellogenic gate without arrest, demonstrating the conditional nature of the gates.

After follicles have separated from the germaria they grow slightly but may soon enter a state of arrest. Follicles in the stage I resting are about 40-50 micrometers long, their epithelia consist of relatively few cells, and their oocytes are visibly distinct but do not contain lipid or others droplets in the ooplasm.

In most anautogenous species, follicles that pass the previtellogenic gate and start to deposit yolk in the oocytes either develop to maturity or are resorbed. There have been a few reports of follicles entering arrest during the course of vitellogenesis, and they indicate the existence of a stage III gate.
The follicle has partly separated from the germarium but the oocyte is not entirely surrounded by epithelium.

Arrestants are substances that induces gravid females to remain in their presence through their own undirected kinetic responses, either by stopping their locomotion or changing their rate of turning.
The follicle has separated from the germarium and the oocyte is entirely surrounded by follicular epithelium. The oocyte is not visibly distinct from the nurse cells.
The oocyte is distinguishable from the nurse cells by its smaller nucleus and prominent nucleolus.
Some very small refractile lipid droplets are visible in the ooplasm.

The ooplasm contains fine lipid droplets, these cause the oocyte to appear slightly dark under transmitted light but white by reflected light. No large droplets are visible in the ooplasm, and no ooplasmic inclusions strain with neutral red.

The ooplasm is clouded with inclusions distinctly. At first the inclusions are small. Subsequently, large yolks spheres appear which stain yellowish-brown with neutral red. These yolk spheres are of smilar diameter to the epithelial cell nucleoli, and are about 0,2 to 0,3 times the diameter of the oocytes' nucleolus. The oocyte's nucleus progressively occupies up to 50% of the length of the follicle.
